\begin_layout Section
Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming the Drude model, it can be shown that (see for example Ashcroft
 and Mermin) the equation of motion per electron becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dp}{dt}=-\frac{p}{\tau}+f
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the force, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is s.t.
 probability of collision of an electron in time 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $dt/\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now consider the situation depicted by the following diagram [taken
 from Ashcroft and Mermin].
 It seems reasonable to imagine that for a fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{x}$
\end_inset

 will depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 by adding to the resistance in some way.
 We therefore define a quantity
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall: In general, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}=\rho\mathbf{j}$
\end_inset

.
 If we consider a typical case (straight wire), we get 
\begin_inset Formula $j=I/A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V=EL$
\end_inset

 and get 
\begin_inset Formula $V=I\rho L/A$
\end_inset

 which using ohms definition, we get the familiar 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\rho L/A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, Magneto-resistance as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(B)=\frac{E_{x}}{j_{x}}
\]

\end_inset

which was experimentally found by Hall to indeed by field dependent.
 Next since by inspection we already know that in steady state, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{y}$
\end_inset

 must balance the lorentz force, which is proportional to both 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and to 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{x}$
\end_inset

, we define a quanitity known as the Hall coeffecient 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{H}=\frac{E_{y}}{j_{x}B}
\]

\end_inset

At this very step, one can make a rather important point.
 The direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{y}$
\end_inset

 depends on whether the charge of the current mediator is positive or negative.
 If the charge is negative, as shown below, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{y}$
\end_inset

 will be negative, and therefore so will 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{H}$
\end_inset

.
 If the charge were positive, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{H}$
\end_inset

 will be positive.
\end_layout

