\begin_layout Standard
We now derive these quantities under the Drude model.
 Let's start with using the equation of motion per electron for an arbitrary
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 field as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\mathbf{p}}{dt}=-e\left(\mathbf{E}+\frac{\mathbf{p}}{mc}\times\mathbf{B}\right)-\frac{\mathbf{p}}{\tau}
\]

\end_inset

In the steady state then, for the given set of fields, we'll have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}0= & -eE_{x}+\cancelto{-\omega_{c}p_{y}}{\left(-\frac{eB}{mc}p_{y}\right)}-\frac{p_{x}}{\tau}\\
0= & -eE_{y}-\cancelto{-\omega_{c}p_{x}}{\left(-\frac{eB}{mc}p_{y}\right)}-\frac{p_{y}}{\tau}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Recall case: Only 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 fields: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}\equiv\rho\mathbf{j}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\equiv1/\rho$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{j}=-ne\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of electrons per unit volume)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the presence of only a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 field, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=-\frac{ne\mathbf{E}\tau}{m}
\]

\end_inset

which entails 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{j}=\frac{-ne^{2}\tau}{m}\mathbf{E}=\sigma\mathbf{E}
\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\frac{ne^{2}\tau}{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Getting back to the equations, we multiply by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{ne\tau}{m}
\]

\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\sigma_{0}E_{x}= & \omega_{c}\tau j_{y}+j_{x}\\
\sigma_{0}E_{y}= & -\omega_{c}\tau j_{x}+j_{y}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{j}=-ne\mathbf{p}/m$
\end_inset

.
 Next we assume that in steady state, 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{y}$
\end_inset

 is zero.
 Plugging this in the previous equations we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\sigma_{0}E_{x}= & j_{x} & \implies E_{x}= & j_{x}\left(\frac{m}{ne^{2}\tau}\right)=j_{x}\rho & \implies & \rho(B)=\frac{m}{ne^{2}\tau}\\
\sigma_{0}E_{y}= & -\omega_{c}\tau j_{x} & \implies E_{y}= & -j_{x}\frac{\cancel{e}B}{\cancel{m}c}\cancel{\tau}\frac{\cancel{m}}{ne^{\cancel{2}}\cancel{\tau}}=j_{x}\left(-\frac{1}{nec}\right)B=j_{x}R_{H}B & \implies & R_{H}=-\frac{1}{nec}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So in accordance with our theory, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(B)$
\end_inset

 doesn't dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, the field.
 This can be verified experimentally.
 Further, it depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 which can depend on various parameters, including temperature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{H}$
\end_inset

 according to the theory is rather boldly predicted to be independent of
 all parameters of the metal, except the electron density.
 This density can be calculated assuming that only the valence electrons
 of the metal participate in the process of metallic conduction.
 However, experimentally it is known that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{H}$
\end_inset

 does depend on the field strength 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experimental Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The setup is as straight forward as it gets.
 We have two electromagnets to produce a strong 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 field.
 Then there's a PCB that holds a crystal which has 5 probes.
 Now this part is slightly new.
 Let me define a convention for clarity.
 The PCB is the 
\begin_inset Formula $x-y$
\end_inset

 plane, the magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is along (or opposite) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Now back to the probes.
 Two of these probes are at horizontally opposite points, say 
\begin_inset Formula $pl$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $pr$
\end_inset

.
 The remaining three probes are along points on the vertically opposite
 edge, of which two are on the top edge, say 
\begin_inset Formula $pt1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $pt2$
\end_inset

, and one probe on the bottom edge 
\begin_inset Formula $pb$
\end_inset

.
 This is a practial requirement.
 We want to find 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(B)$
\end_inset

 for which, by definition of these quantities, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 These quantities are measured using potential differences and currents.
 Infact, I use a current source to pass current horizontally through the
 crystal.
 Next, we note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{\partial V}{\partial x}=E_{x};-\frac{\partial V}{\partial y}=E_{y}
\]

\end_inset

which entails that if I wish to measure the voltage difference between two
 pionts on vertically opposite edges, unless the points have identical 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coordinates, there'll be a potential difference along 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 which will be read, in addition to the vertical difference.
 In practice, it is nearly impossible to achieve zero difference in the
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coordinate.
 Thus, we use two probes on the top edge and take an appropriate linear
 combination (done using a potentiometer) to effectively make the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coordinate of the two points zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So much for the five probes.
 Now back to the discussion of the remaining setup.
 We are given a gauss meter to measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 field in a high precision (
\begin_inset Formula $\times1$
\end_inset

) and a low precision (larger range) mode 
\begin_inset Formula $(\times10)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\times1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\times10$
\end_inset

 mean that whatever answer the meter reads, you multiply it by 1 and 10
 respectively.
 This means the latter is low precision.
 It's easy to confuse it to mean magnification 
\begin_inset Formula $1x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $10x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We are also given a current source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Final Formulae
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want our formulae in a form that's in terms of easier observables.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}E_{x}l_{x} & =V_{x}\\
E_{y}l_{y} & =V_{H}\\
j_{x} & =I/A=I/l_{y}l_{z}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Now recall the definitions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\rho(B) & =\frac{E_{x}}{j_{x}}\\
 & =\frac{V_{x}}{l_{x}(I/l_{y}l_{z})}\\
 & =\frac{V_{x}l_{y}l_{z}}{l_{x}I}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}R_{H} & =\frac{E_{y}}{j_{x}B}\\
 & =\frac{V_{H}l_{z}\cancel{l_{y}}}{IB\cancel{l_{y}}}\\
 & =\frac{V_{H}l_{z}}{IB}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

To be consistent with the manual, I define 
\begin_inset Formula $t\equiv l_{z}=0.5mm,\,b\equiv l_{x}=6mm,\,l\equiv l_{y}=7mm$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

