\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calibrating the Guass Meter and the Electromagnets
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Take the gauss meter sufficiently far away from the electromagnet and calibrate
 it to read zero in high precision (x1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Bring the electromagnets faces sufficiently
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
such that if you place the PCB between the faces, it almost touches the
 PCB and the crystal on opposite ends, but doesn't infact.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 close.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now place the gauss meter between the two faces of the electromagnet, parallel
 to it, with the electromagnet switched off.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the gauss meter reads a non-zero value (this may happen because of hysterisis
) then
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Put the gauss meter in the low precision mode
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Turn on the electromagnet and try changing the current/voltage through the
 coil to get the value as close to zero as possible; if the value drops
 to zero in (
\begin_inset Formula $\times10$
\end_inset

, then goto high precision and repeat) [this should not work]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the previous step failed, as it should
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
because it is designed to produce a large field.
 To exactly cancel the stray field, we must get the coils to produce opposite
 fields so that their superposition yields a small adjustable field
\end_layout

\end_inset

, in one of the coils, swap the wires (do not swap wires from distinct coils,
 it'll just result in reversing the direction of the large field) and try
 the previous step.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Now keep the gauss meter away (viz.
 don't keep it where it has been designed to keep according to the setup)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Setting up the crystal, its current source and volt meter
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Now with the current source off, put the PCB between the electromagnet's
 faces such that the PCB is parallel to the faces and the crystal is in
 the centre.
 Ensure that neither the PCB nor the crystal touch the electromagnet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the terminals aren't connected, connect them in accordance with the labels
 on the PCB.
 The reasoning should be obvious by now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To be certain, before turning on the current source, stick in the gauss
 meter, once behind the PCB and once in front of the crystal and ensure
 the field is zero.
 If it is not, repeat the previous set of steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now start the current source at some low value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Look at the reading on the voltmeter.
 If this were indeed measuring the Hall voltage, it should be zero since
 the magnetic field is zero.
 The reading in practice won't be zero (excluding exceptional circumstances)
 because of the longitudinal voltage as explained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now change the 'Zero adj.' potentiometer on the PCB to get the reading to
 be zero.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

If the range of the potentiometer exhausts and you're not able to achieve
 a zero then
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Power off the PCB and carefully loosen the 
\begin_inset Formula $pb$
\end_inset

 probe
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Readjust it to be almost opposite to the midpoint of 
\begin_inset Formula $pt1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $pt2$
\end_inset

 probes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Try the zero adjustment again.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
To be certain that the zero adjustment is reliable, increase the current
 from the current source and record the readings on the voltmeter.
 This should remain roughly zero.
 Tabulate the data.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Finding 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{H}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Set the field to be over 1,500 Gauss (low precision should read 150)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Keep the PCB powered off.
 Measure the magnetic field at both behind the PCB and in front of the crystal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now power the PCB by sweeping the current and measure the corresponding
 value of voltage on the voltmeter (which we now know is reliably, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{H}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Measure the field again to be certain nothing went wrong.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
